## Introduction
Projectiles include arrows, snowballs, eggs, fireballs, and more. You can listen to events when they hit entities or blocks.

### Example: Detect Arrow Hit
```java
@EventHandler
public void onProjectileHit(ProjectileHitEvent event) {
    Projectile projectile = event.getEntity();
    if(projectile instanceof Arrow arrow) {
        if(arrow.getShooter() instanceof Player player) {
            player.sendMessage("Your arrow hit something!");
        }
    }
}
```

### Logic Explanation
- `ProjectileHitEvent` triggers when a projectile hits something.
- Use `instanceof` to determine projectile type.
- `getShooter()` lets you identify the player who shot it.

### Edge Cases & Warnings
- Some projectiles may hit entities or blocks differently.
- Projectiles like fireballs have explosive effects; handle with care.
- Null checks are important; `getShooter()` may not always return a player.

## Introduction
You can add custom effects when projectiles hit entities or blocks.

### Example: Exploding Snowball
```java
@EventHandler
public void onSnowballHit(ProjectileHitEvent event) {
    if(event.getEntity() instanceof Snowball) {
        Location loc = event.getEntity().getLocation();
        loc.getWorld().createExplosion(loc.getX(), loc.getY(), loc.getZ(), 2.0f, false, false);
    }
}
```

### Logic Explanation
- Check projectile type with `instanceof`.
- Use `createExplosion(x, y, z, power, setFire, breakBlocks)` for custom effects.
- Can trigger sounds, particles, or potion effects as well.

### Edge Cases & Warnings
- Explosions may damage terrain or entities; use `setFire` and `breakBlocks` carefully.
- Test server performance with multiple projectiles.
- Some effects may need permission checks or cooldowns.
